            {
              "id": "00a8124b-8ae7-32eb-a2de-6e4da33a07db",
              "name": "Unsanitized User-Influenced Filename Vulnerability in Content-Disposition Header",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsanitized User-Influenced Filename Vulnerability in Content-Disposition Header\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when user-influenced data is used to construct a filename in the `Content-Disposition` HTTP header without proper sanitization. This can lead to various attacks such as HTTP response splitting, HTTP header injection, or other injection attacks.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the filename for the `Content-Disposition` header is constructed using the `node[client.NodeSpecFieldRequestedHostname]` value, which could be influenced by the user. If this value is not properly sanitized, it could lead to the mentioned attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to sanitize the user-influenced data before using it to construct the filename. This can be done by removing or encoding special characters that could be used in injection attacks, such as newlines, carriage returns, or quotes.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix using the `path` package to sanitize the filename:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"fmt\"\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"path\"\n)\n\nfunc setHeader(apiContext *http.Context, node map[string]string) {\n    filename := path.Base(node[client.NodeSpecFieldRequestedHostname])\n    apiContext.Response.Header().Set(\"Content-Disposition\", fmt.Sprintf(\"attachment; filename=%s.zip\", filename))\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `path.Base` function is used to sanitize the filename by removing any directory components.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `net/http`\n- `path`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-113: Improper Neutralization of CRLF Sequences in HTTP Headers ('HTTP Response Splitting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-113",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-113"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "02deea5e-49de-3b31-80b7-607fc0ac2588",
              "name": "Manual JWT token decoding vulnerability due to lack of cryptographic signature verification.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Manual JWT token decoding vulnerability due to lack of cryptographic signature verification\" refers to a situation where a JSON Web Token (JWT) is manually decoded without verifying its cryptographic signature. This can lead to security issues as an attacker can modify the payload of the JWT and the server would accept it as a valid token.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the JWT token is split into its components and the payload is base64 decoded and unmarshalled into a map without any signature verification. This means that the integrity of the token is not checked, making it susceptible to tampering.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always verify the signature of the JWT before decoding it. This ensures that the token has not been tampered with and is from a trusted source. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nYou can use the `jwt-go` library to parse and verify the JWT. Here is an example of how to do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n\t\"github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\"\n)\n\nfunc ParseToken(tokenString string) (map[string]interface{}, error) {\n\ttoken, err := jwt.Parse(tokenString, func(token *jwt.Token) (interface{}, error) {\n\t\t// Don't forget to validate the alg is what you expect:\n\t\tif _, ok := token.Method.(*jwt.SigningMethodHMAC); !ok {\n\t\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"Unexpected signing method: %v\", token.Header[\"alg\"])\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn []byte(\"your-256-bit-secret\"), nil\n\t})\n\n\tif claims, ok := token.Claims.(jwt.MapClaims); ok && token.Valid {\n\t\treturn claims, nil\n\t} else {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `jwt.Parse` is used to parse and verify the JWT. The function provided to `jwt.Parse` is used to return the key for signature verification. Replace `\"your-256-bit-secret\"` with your actual secret key.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP JWT Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/JSON_Web_Token_Cheat_Sheet_for_Java.html)\n- [CWE-347: Improper Verification of Cryptographic Signature](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/347.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-347",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/347.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-347"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "06623b00-fbe7-3f9f-9100-9faa9f698d05",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data like authentication keys, passwords, or tokens are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive data. These methods allow you to change the credentials without modifying the code and also keep the credentials out of the source code repository.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret type, you can use environment variables to store the secret type. Here is an example of how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nvar AuthConfigSecretType string\n\nfunc init() {\n    AuthConfigSecretType = os.Getenv(\"AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_TYPE\")\n    if AuthConfigSecretType == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"missing environment variable AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_TYPE\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_TYPE` environment variable is used to store the secret type. The `os.Getenv` function is used to get the value of the environment variable. If the environment variable is not set, the program will log a fatal error and exit.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any additional library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0769af76-8832-3a59-80e4-3bccc43bfba0",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0998714a-d134-3483-961b-c4f4f34d3812",
              "name": "Unencrypted LDAP Connection Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnencrypted LDAP Connection Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the security risk associated with establishing a connection to an LDAP server without using encryption. This can expose sensitive information, such as usernames and passwords, to potential eavesdroppers on the network. The vulnerability sink in this case is the `ldapv3.Dial` function, which is used to establish a connection to an LDAP server.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use encrypted connections when communicating with an LDAP server. This can be achieved by using the `DialTLS` function instead of the `Dial` function. The `DialTLS` function establishes a connection to the server using the LDAP over TLS (Transport Layer Security) protocol, which provides encryption.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the `Dial` function with the `DialTLS` function:\n\n```go\nlConn, err = ldapv3.DialTLS(\"tcp\", fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%d\", server, port), &tls.Config{InsecureSkipVerify: true})\n```\n\nNote: The `InsecureSkipVerify: true` option is used here for simplicity, but in a production environment, you should use a valid certificate and set `InsecureSkipVerify: false`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- `github.com/go-ldap/ldap/v3`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - LDAP Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/LDAP_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "11766571-279f-3935-8f3c-cf5c732407ff",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the application's source code. This is a serious issue because if the source code is ever exposed or leaked, an attacker could easily extract these secrets and use them to gain unauthorized access to systems or data.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability could occur if sensitive data is hardcoded into the source code, as shown in the provided code snippet.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, sensitive data should never be hardcoded into the source code. Instead, it should be stored securely and retrieved as needed, for example, through environment variables or secure configuration files. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret into the source code, you can use environment variables to store and retrieve the secret. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    secret := os.Getenv(\"SECRET\")\n    // Use the secret\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv(\"SECRET\")` retrieves the value of the `SECRET` environment variable. You can set this environment variable in your server's configuration.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A3 - Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "11b7a10f-bee0-32d5-8f78-0465816f32c8",
              "name": "\"Gorilla Session.Get() Error Ignored Leading to Unauthenticated User Treated as Authenticated\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Gorilla Session.Get() error ignored leading to unauthenticated user treated as authenticated is a vulnerability in Go programming language that occurs when the error returned by the `Get()` function of the Gorilla Session package is ignored. This can lead to a situation where an unauthenticated user is treated as authenticated, leading to potential unauthorized access to sensitive information or functionality.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is important to always handle the error returned by the `Get()` function. If the function returns an error, the session should not be used, as it may not be valid. Instead, the error should be logged and the user should be treated as unauthenticated.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```go\ncluster, err := ch.Clusters.Get(clusterID, metav1.GetOptions{})\nif err != nil {\n    // Handle error, for example log it and return\n    log.Println(err)\n    return\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the error returned by the `Get()` function is stored in the `err` variable. The error is then checked, and if it is not `nil`, it is logged and the function returns.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- github.com/gorilla/sessions\n- k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [A2:2017-Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-287: Improper Authentication](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/287.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-390",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/390.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-390"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "13f8d885-5b72-3b5e-9784-9b86839cac16",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or secrets are hardcoded into the application's source code. This is a common issue in Go programming language as well as other languages. The problem arises when an attacker gains access to the source code, they can easily extract these hardcoded sensitive data and use them for malicious purposes.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `IdentityTokenAuthConfigSecretKey` is hardcoded as \"identityToken\", which is a clear example of this vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding sensitive data in the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store these data. These methods allow you to change the sensitive data without changing the source code and also keep them out of the source code, making it harder for an attacker to gain access to them.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the `IdentityTokenAuthConfigSecretKey`, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here is how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nIdentityTokenAuthConfigSecretKey := os.Getenv(\"IDENTITY_TOKEN_SECRET_KEY\")\n```\n\nIn this code, `IDENTITY_TOKEN_SECRET_KEY` is an environment variable that stores the secret key. You can set this environment variable in your server or local machine where you run the application.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10-2017 A3-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "147f0adc-a1c6-3f12-8e86-b39df5b04ced",
              "name": "\"Host Key Verification Disabled, Allowing Man-in-the-Middle Attacks\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Host Key Verification Disabled, Allowing Man-in-the-Middle Attacks\" occurs when the SSH client is configured to skip the host key verification process. This is a serious security issue as it allows an attacker to intercept the SSH connection, posing as the intended server (a Man-in-the-Middle attack). The attacker can then gain access to sensitive information or inject malicious data.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `HostKeyCallback` function is set to `ssh.InsecureIgnoreHostKey()`, which instructs the SSH client to ignore the host key verification process.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, the SSH client should be configured to perform host key verification. This can be done by setting the `HostKeyCallback` function to `ssh.FixedHostKey()`, which requires a known host key. If the host key provided by the server does not match the known host key, the SSH client will refuse to connect.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace `ssh.InsecureIgnoreHostKey()` with `ssh.FixedHostKey()`. Here is an example:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"golang.org/x/crypto/ssh\"\n\t\"golang.org/x/crypto/ssh/knownhosts\"\n\t\"log\"\n\t\"net\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\thostKeyCallback, err := knownhosts.New(\"/.ssh/known_hosts\")\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n\t}\n\n\tconfig := &ssh.ClientConfig{\n\t\tUser: \"user\",\n\t\tAuth: []ssh.AuthMethod{\n\t\t\tssh.Password(\"password\"),\n\t\t},\n\t\tHostKeyCallback: hostKeyCallback,\n\t}\n\n\t_, err = ssh.Dial(\"tcp\", \"localhost:22\", config)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlog.Fatal(\"Failed to dial: \", err)\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n- golang.org/x/crypto/ssh\n- golang.org/x/crypto/ssh/knownhosts\n- log\n- net\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Configuration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n- [CWE-295: Improper Certificate Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-322",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/322.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-322"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "17ecc46f-6dbe-34a9-a76c-8b6abb21feb8",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
