            {
              "id": "1ddce8bb-2af9-3717-a411-670e470c584b",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data such as API keys, database credentials, or other secrets are hardcoded into the program.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials in your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive information. These methods allow you to separate your credentials from your source code, making it harder for an attacker to gain access to them.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secrets namespace, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    SecretsNamespace := os.Getenv(\"SECRETS_NAMESPACE\")\n    // rest of your code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `SECRETS_NAMESPACE` is an environment variable that you can set in your server or development environment. This way, the actual value of the secret is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
