            {
              "id": "1f1a774c-a8c1-3cab-b92f-e877b8f6d74c",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or secrets are hardcoded into the application's source code. This is a common issue in Go programming language as well as other languages. The problem arises when an attacker gains access to the source code, they can easily extract these hardcoded secrets and use them to gain unauthorized access to systems or services.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data in the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this information. These methods allow you to separate the sensitive data from the code, making it harder for an attacker to gain access to it.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key in the source code, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here is how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    appSecretKey := os.Getenv(\"APP_SECRET_KEY\")\n    if appSecretKey == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"APP_SECRET_KEY is required\")\n    }\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv` is used to get the value of the `APP_SECRET_KEY` environment variable. If the variable is not set, the program will terminate with an error message.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A3 - Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "244cde75-b9ae-3d9a-9d85-772b3d548eba",
              "name": "Unencrypted LDAP Connection Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unencrypted LDAP Connection Vulnerability\" in Go programming language refers to the security risk associated with establishing a connection to an LDAP server without using encryption. This can expose sensitive data, such as usernames and passwords, to potential eavesdroppers who can intercept the traffic between the client and the server.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use encrypted connections when communicating with an LDAP server. This can be achieved by using the `DialTLS` function instead of the `Dial` function. The `DialTLS` function establishes a secure connection to the server using the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to establish a secure connection to an LDAP server using the `DialTLS` function:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/tls\"\n    \"fmt\"\n    \"gopkg.in/ldap.v3\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    server := \"ldap.example.com\"\n    port := 636\n\n    tlsConfig := &tls.Config{InsecureSkipVerify: true}\n    lConn, err := ldap.DialTLS(\"tcp\", fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%d\", server, port), tlsConfig)\n    if err != nil {\n        log.Fatal(err)\n    }\n    defer lConn.Close()\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `InsecureSkipVerify` field is set to `true` to disable server name verification, which is not recommended for production code. In a production environment, you should use a valid certificate and set `InsecureSkipVerify` to `false`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go package:\n\n- `gopkg.in/ldap.v3`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2594e6ea-eb8d-3e9b-86d1-ad28b6bbddb5",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration leading to insecure default value",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `tls.Config` struct is used to configure TLS clients and servers. If the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` is not set, the Go runtime will default to `SSLv3.0`. This is a security vulnerability because SSLv3.0 is considered insecure and has been deprecated. An attacker can exploit this to perform a downgrade attack, forcing the connection to use the insecure SSLv3.0 protocol.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` to a secure value. The recommended minimum version is `tls.VersionTLS12`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs: certPool,\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "26d467d5-6e90-319e-a5f5-a967a488f59b",
              "name": "\"TLS Certificate Verification Disabled, Allowing MITM Attacks\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `InsecureSkipVerify` option in the `tls.Config` struct of Go's `crypto/tls` package controls whether a client verifies the server's certificate chain and host name. If `InsecureSkipVerify` is `true`, TLS accepts any certificate presented by the server and any host name in that certificate. In this mode, TLS is susceptible to man-in-the-middle attacks. This should be used only for testing.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe `InsecureSkipVerify` option should be set to `false` in production code. This ensures that the client verifies the server's certificate chain and host name. If the server's certificate is self-signed, you can add the public key to your trusted CA pool.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-295: Improper Certificate Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-295",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-295"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2c63bb3e-d0da-36fa-a4a3-cffa3964e229",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed, as the credentials are easily readable and accessible. In the provided code snippet, the `AuthTokenResourceName` variable is hardcoded, which could potentially be a security risk.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vault services to store and access such information. These methods allow you to keep your sensitive data separate from your source code, reducing the risk of it being exposed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the `AuthTokenResourceName`, you can use an environment variable to store this value. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nvar AuthTokenResourceName string\n\nfunc init() {\n    AuthTokenResourceName = os.Getenv(\"AUTH_TOKEN_RESOURCE_NAME\")\n    if AuthTokenResourceName == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"$AUTH_TOKEN_RESOURCE_NAME must be set\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `AuthTokenResourceName` is retrieved from the `AUTH_TOKEN_RESOURCE_NAME` environment variable. If the environment variable is not set, the program will log a fatal error and exit.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Security Credentials](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
