            {
              "id": "2cf567c6-d956-329b-ad06-fc150e2a22e7",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable\" is a vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials are hardcoded directly into the source code. This is a bad practice as it exposes sensitive data to anyone who has access to the source code. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when credentials are stored in package-level variables.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to avoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive data. These methods allow you to change the data without modifying the code and also keep the data out of the source code, reducing the risk of exposure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the password change request resource name into the source code, you can store it in an environment variable. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nvar PasswordChangeRequestResourceName string\n\nfunc init() {\n    PasswordChangeRequestResourceName = os.Getenv(\"PASSWORD_CHANGE_REQUEST_RESOURCE_NAME\")\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `PASSWORD_CHANGE_REQUEST_RESOURCE_NAME` environment variable is used to store the password change request resource name. The `init` function is a special function in Go that is called when the package is initialized. This function is used to initialize the `PasswordChangeRequestResourceName` variable with the value of the `PASSWORD_CHANGE_REQUEST_RESOURCE_NAME` environment variable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any library dependencies other than the standard \"os\" package provided by Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
