            {
              "id": "300bc5a6-cb0c-30ea-a3a8-46c72df97915",
              "name": "\"MD5's Cryptographic Vulnerability: Inappropriate for Security-Sensitive Uses; Use bcrypt, argon2id, SHA-256, or SHA-3 Instead\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hashing algorithm is considered cryptographically broken and unsuitable for further use. Its main weakness is that it's vulnerable to hash collisions, where different inputs produce the same hash output. This makes it inappropriate for functions such as SSL certificates or encryption that require a unique and secure hash. \n\nIn the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 checksum (a widely used cryptographic hash function) of a data. However, due to the vulnerabilities associated with MD5, it's not recommended for security-sensitive uses.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nFor security-sensitive uses, consider using stronger hash functions such as bcrypt, argon2id, SHA-256, or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered to be much more secure and resistant to hash collisions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of MD5 with a more secure hash function. Here's an example of how to use SHA-256 instead:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `crypto/sha256` package is used to compute the SHA-256 checksum. The `encoding/hex` package is used to convert the checksum to a hexadecimal string.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-328",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-328"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3143a525-cbbd-3829-8a3f-07b7f0349224",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly within the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data like API keys, passwords, or secret keys are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vault systems to store and access these credentials. Ensure these methods are secure and encrypted to prevent unauthorized access.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly in the code:\n\n```go\nAuthConfigConditionSecretsMigrated condition.Cond = \"SecretsMigrated\"\n```\n\nYou can use environment variables to store the secret:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nAuthConfigConditionSecretsMigrated condition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"SECRETS_MIGRATED\")\n```\n\nIn this case, `SECRETS_MIGRATED` is an environment variable that stores the secret. This way, the secret is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not provide enough context to determine the specific library dependencies required. However, the `os` package is a standard library in Go and does not require any additional dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "316ac553-2e84-3474-aecb-24e480db45d9",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common issue in many programming languages, including Go. If an attacker gains access to the source code, they can easily extract these secrets and use them for malicious purposes.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `ClusterConditionSecretsMigrated` variable is assigned a hardcoded value. If this value is a secret or sensitive data, it could be exposed if an attacker gains access to the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data in the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store and retrieve these values. These methods allow you to change the values without modifying the source code and can provide additional layers of security.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the value, you can retrieve it from an environment variable. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    ClusterConditionSecretsMigrated := os.Getenv(\"SECRETS_MIGRATED\")\n    condition.Cond = ClusterConditionSecretsMigrated\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `SECRETS_MIGRATED` is an environment variable that stores the secret value. You can set this environment variable in your server or development environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A3:2017-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
