            {
              "id": "36f1f6b3-b371-3375-b5b7-b370bc605ea9",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed, as the credentials are easily readable. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data like passwords, API keys, or secrets are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, external configuration files, or secure vaults to store this information. This not only makes your application more secure, but also more flexible, as you can change the credentials without having to modify and recompile the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key in the source code, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    PasswordAuthConfigSecretKey := os.Getenv(\"PASSWORD_AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_KEY\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv` is used to get the value of the `PASSWORD_AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_KEY` environment variable. You can set this environment variable in your server or local development environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Password](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
