            {
              "id": "3df47109-e391-322b-af2a-aa66d348258d",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure due to its vulnerability to collision attacks, where two different inputs produce the same hash output. This can lead to various security issues such as data integrity violation and unauthorized information disclosure. In Go programming language, if you are using `md5.Sum(bytes)` to generate hash values, it is recommended to replace it with a more secure hash algorithm like SHA256 or SHA3.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should replace the MD5 hash algorithm with a more secure one, such as SHA256 or SHA3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not vulnerable to collision attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the MD5 hash algorithm with SHA256 or SHA3. Here is an example of how to do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    data := []byte(\"your data\")\n    hash := sha256.Sum256(data)\n    hashString := hex.EncodeToString(hash[:])\n    fmt.Println(hashString)\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `crypto/sha256` package is used to generate a SHA256 hash of the input data. The `encoding/hex` package is used to convert the hash to a hexadecimal string.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3ff82e76-37b0-3c60-a5de-63293f03d714",
              "name": "\"Detected Session Cookie Lacks 'HttpOnly' Flag\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Detected Session Cookie Lacks 'HttpOnly' Flag\" vulnerability refers to a situation where a session cookie is set without the 'HttpOnly' flag. This can potentially expose the cookie to cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks, as the flag is meant to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when creating a new cookie using the `http.Cookie` struct without setting the `HttpOnly` field to `true`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `HttpOnly` field to `true` when creating a new cookie. This will prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, thus reducing the risk of XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nr.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n    Name:     \"R_OIDC_ID\",\n    Value:    \"test-id-token\",\n    HttpOnly: true,\n})\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, the `HttpOnly` field is set to `true`, which means the cookie cannot be accessed through client-side scripts.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly. It only uses the `http` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://owasp.org/www-community/HttpOnly)\n- [CWE-1004: Sensitive Cookie Without 'HttpOnly' Flag](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1004.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1004",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1004.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-1004"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "434abbb9-188d-36ae-a69f-492d253bdae6",
              "name": "\"Session Cookie Lacks 'HttpOnly' Flag Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Session Cookie Lacks 'HttpOnly' Flag\" vulnerability refers to a situation where a session cookie does not have the 'HttpOnly' flag set. This flag is a security measure that helps mitigate the risk of cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks. When the 'HttpOnly' flag is set, it prevents the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts. Without this flag, an attacker could potentially steal the session cookie through an XSS attack, leading to session hijacking.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always set the 'HttpOnly' flag for session cookies. This can be done by setting the 'HttpOnly' field of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nreq.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n    Name:     \"R_OIDC_ID\",\n    Value:    \"test-id-token\",\n    HttpOnly: true,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the built-in `net/http` package of the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://owasp.org/www-community/HttpOnly)\n- [CWE-1004: Sensitive Cookie Without 'HttpOnly' Flag](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1004.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1004",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1004.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-1004"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4393527b-5195-37bb-adda-e70a8a4eb059",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "43abe175-6607-3765-bd02-f8cdc5f4e2e1",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. In the context of Go programming language, an XSS vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is not properly escaped before being included in an HTTP response. This can allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts into the HTTP response, which are then executed by the user's browser.\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in question is:\n\n```go\nresp.Write([]byte(err.Error()))\n```\n\nIn this case, the error message (`err.Error()`) is directly written into the HTTP response without any sanitization or escaping. If the error message contains user-controlled data, this could lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled data before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"html\"\n\n// ...\n\nerrorMessage := html.EscapeString(err.Error())\nresp.Write([]byte(errorMessage))\n```\n\nIn this version, the `html.EscapeString` function is used to escape any special characters in the error message before it is included in the HTTP response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code example requires the `html` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "468007b2-7477-3472-88ef-f5f7d32be082",
              "name": "Unintended Public Server Exposure due to Binding to All Interfaces",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the vulnerability \"Unintended Public Server Exposure due to Binding to All Interfaces\" occurs when a network service is unintentionally exposed to the public internet. This happens when the service binds to all network interfaces (0.0.0.0 or ::), instead of binding to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1). This can lead to unauthorized access to the service, data leakage, or even remote code execution.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `net.Listen(\"tcp\", \":0\")` function call binds the listener to all network interfaces, which can expose the server to the public internet.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should bind your service to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1) unless it is necessary for the service to be accessible from the public internet. This will ensure that the service is only accessible from the local machine.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nlistener, err := net.Listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:0\") // bind to localhost and choose any available port\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet only requires the `net` package from the standard library of Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-284: Improper Access Control](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/284.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "47deec71-9e6a-3a6e-b551-b2a568d3a991",
              "name": "Unintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a situation where an attacker can manipulate the control flow of a program. This can lead to unexpected behavior, including unauthorized access or privilege escalation. In the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the use of the `FieldByName` method, which can be exploited if an attacker can control the `key` variable.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate and sanitize all inputs. Avoid using user-controlled data to determine the control flow of the application. If the use of such methods is unavoidable, ensure that the application correctly handles all possible inputs.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly using the user-controlled `key` variable, validate it against a list of allowed values before using it in `FieldByName` method.\n\n```go\nallowedKeys := map[string]bool{\n    \"allowedKey1\": true,\n    \"allowedKey2\": true,\n    // add more allowed keys here\n}\n\nif _, ok := allowedKeys[key]; ok {\n    secret := clusterSecrets.FieldByName(key)\n    // rest of the code\n} else {\n    log.Println(\"Invalid key: \", key)\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the required library dependencies. However, the `FieldByName` method is a part of the `reflect` package in Go, so this package is likely to be required.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-807: Reliance on Untrusted Inputs in a Security Decision](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/807.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-470",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/470.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-470"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "47f08174-fee7-359d-b883-ac99c9fae4bf",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common issue in many programming languages, including Go. \n\nIn the provided code snippet, the string \"RKESecretsMigrated\" is hardcoded into the source code. If this string is a secret, such as an API key or a password, this would be a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to avoid hardcoding sensitive data into the source code. Instead, sensitive data should be stored in a secure manner, such as in environment variables or secure configuration files. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the string \"RKESecretsMigrated\", it should be stored in a secure manner. Here is an example of how to do this using environment variables in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    condition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"RKESecretsMigrated\")\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the secret is stored in an environment variable named \"RKESecretsMigrated\". This way, the secret is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP: Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "48b338fb-e58f-33df-822d-fc30d08726c4",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed, as the credentials are easily readable. In the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data like OAuth credentials are hardcoded into the application.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this information. These methods allow you to change the credentials without modifying the code and also keep the credentials out of the source code repository.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the OAuth credentials, you can use environment variables to store these credentials. Here is how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    oauthCredential := os.Getenv(\"OAUTH_CREDENTIAL\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `OAUTH_CREDENTIAL` is an environment variable that stores the OAuth credential. You can set this environment variable in your server or local machine where the application is running.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `os` package which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
