            {
              "id": "5208eccb-1dc1-336b-a924-49fa3d6cc182",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data such as API keys, database credentials, or other secrets are hardcoded into the application.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials in your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive information. These methods allow you to separate your credentials from your source code, making it harder for an attacker to gain access to them.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code snippet is the hardcoded string \"ServiceAccountSecretsMigrated\". This string could potentially be a secret or a credential that should not be hardcoded. Here is a way to fix this:\n\n```go\n// Define the condition as a constant or an environment variable\nconst ServiceAccountSecretsMigrated = \"ServiceAccountSecretsMigrated\"\n\n// Use the constant or environment variable in your code\nClusterConditionServiceAccountSecretsMigrated condition.Cond = ServiceAccountSecretsMigrated\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the library dependencies. However, it seems to be using a custom `condition` package. You would need to import this package at the beginning of your Go file:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"yourpath/condition\"\n)\n```\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Security Credentials](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "52965fe0-baeb-367d-93e7-d013814ffbc8",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common issue in many programming languages, including Go. If an attacker gains access to the source code, they can easily extract these hardcoded values and use them to gain unauthorized access to systems or data.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, `AuthConfigSecretType = \"rke.cattle.io/auth-config\"` is a hardcoded value that could potentially be a security vulnerability if it is a sensitive piece of information.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data in the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this information. These methods allow you to change the values without modifying the code and also keep the sensitive data out of the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the `AuthConfigSecretType`, you can use an environment variable to store this value. Here is how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nAuthConfigSecretType := os.Getenv(\"AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_TYPE\")\n```\n\nIn this code, `AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_TYPE` is an environment variable that stores the value of `AuthConfigSecretType`. You can set this environment variable in your server or development environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A3 - Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
