              "id": "5529c5cf-938a-3caf-9213-5f7fea995766",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data such as API keys, database credentials, or other secrets are hardcoded into the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials in your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vault systems to store and access sensitive data. Ensure that these storage mechanisms are properly secured to prevent unauthorized access.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink provided does not seem to contain hardcoded credentials. However, if it did, a potential fix could look like this:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    condition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"RKESecretsMigrated\")\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `os.Getenv` function is used to retrieve the value of the `RKESecretsMigrated` environment variable. This value should be set in the environment where the application is running, not in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe specific code example does not seem to require any library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A2-Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [OWASP Cheat Sheet: Password Storage](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
