            {
              "id": "558362ce-d7c6-34db-90d9-6835ea668c25",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common issue in many programming languages, including Go. \n\nHardcoding sensitive information in the source code is a bad practice because it exposes the data to anyone who has access to the source code. This could include other developers, version control systems, or even attackers if the source code is leaked or publicly accessible. \n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `ClusterPrivateRegistrySecret` variable is hardcoded with the value `\"PrivateRegistrySecret\"`. This could potentially be a sensitive piece of information that should not be exposed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, sensitive data should never be hardcoded into the source code. Instead, it should be stored securely and retrieved through secure means. \n\nIn Go, you can use environment variables to store sensitive data. Environment variables are a good choice because they are not typically stored with the source code and can be set per environment. This means that you can have different values for development, testing, and production environments.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the `ClusterPrivateRegistrySecret` value, you can retrieve it from an environment variable:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    ClusterPrivateRegistrySecret := os.Getenv(\"PRIVATE_REGISTRY_SECRET\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv` is used to retrieve the value of the `PRIVATE_REGISTRY_SECRET` environment variable. This value can be set in the environment where the application is running.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the built-in `os` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A3:2017-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
