            {
              "id": "57732480-ce41-329c-bcc4-f969879c3f3d",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data like access keys, passwords, or API keys are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive data. These methods allow you to separate your credentials from your source code, reducing the risk of exposure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the credentials, you can use environment variables to store them. Here is an example of how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n    \"log\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    accessKey, exists := os.LookupEnv(\"ACCESS_KEY\")\n    if !exists {\n        log.Fatal(\"ACCESS_KEY not set in environment\")\n    }\n    // Use accessKey\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the access key is read from the environment variable `ACCESS_KEY`. If the environment variable is not set, the program will log a fatal error and exit.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the standard `os` and `log` packages provided by Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
