            {
              "id": "5f47d9c9-111d-3fa5-9d95-1223cc72a774",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data like passwords, API keys, or other credentials are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials in your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive information. These methods allow you to separate your credentials from your source code, making it harder for an attacker to gain unauthorized access.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the password namespace, you can use an environment variable to store this sensitive information. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    LocalUserPasswordsNamespace := os.Getenv(\"PASSWORD_NAMESPACE\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `PASSWORD_NAMESPACE` is an environment variable that stores the password namespace. You can set this environment variable in your server or local development environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `os` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
