            {
              "id": "6222aa12-116a-3b7c-9964-09aab18537df",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data such as passwords, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded directly into the source code.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the string \"SecretsMigrated\" is hardcoded. If this string is a secret or a credential, it could lead to a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials or secrets directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store and access these sensitive data. \n\nEnsure that these data are encrypted at rest and in transit. Use secure methods to access these data, such as secure APIs or services that provide access control and auditing.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the string directly, consider using an environment variable to store the secret. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    condition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"SECRETS_MIGRATED\")\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `SECRETS_MIGRATED` is an environment variable that stores the secret. The `os.Getenv` function retrieves the value of the environment variable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not indicate any specific library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
