            {
              "id": "6390bc16-96d8-35dd-81b1-093119afda04",
              "name": "Automatic exposure of 'pprof' profiling endpoint could lead to server information leakage. Use `import \"net/http/pprof\"` for mitigation.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `net/http/pprof` package automatically registers its handlers with the default HTTP mux. If the application is using the default mux and serving on a public address, this could lead to the exposure of profiling data to the public. This is a security vulnerability as it could lead to server information leakage.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the default mux for your application. Instead, create a new mux and register your handlers with it. This way, the `pprof` handlers will not be exposed on the public address.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is a code fix for the vulnerability:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"net/http/pprof\"\n    \"log\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    mux := http.NewServeMux()\n\n    // Register your handlers here\n    // mux.HandleFunc(\"/\", yourHandler)\n\n    // Create a new server and set the mux\n    server := &http.Server{\n        Addr:    profileAddress,\n        Handler: mux,\n    }\n\n    log.Println(server.ListenAndServe())\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, a new mux is created and the server is set to use this mux. The `pprof` handlers are not registered with this mux, so they will not be exposed on the public address.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `net/http/pprof`\n- `log`\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "687786fd-5223-37d6-b833-14834d0fca8b",
              "name": "Unintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a situation where an attacker can manipulate the control flow of a Go application, leading to unexpected behavior. This can occur when user-supplied input is used to construct a field name for reflection-based access, such as `status.FieldByName(key)`. If the `key` is controlled by the user, they can potentially access any field in the `status` object, leading to information disclosure or other unintended consequences.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it's recommended to avoid using user-supplied input to control the flow of the application, especially when using reflection. If it's necessary to use user input in this way, ensure that it's properly sanitized and validated before use. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly using the user-supplied `key` to access a field in the `status` object, validate the `key` against a list of allowed values. Here's an example of how you might do this:\n\n```go\nallowedKeys := map[string]bool{\n    \"allowedField1\": true,\n    \"allowedField2\": true,\n    // add more allowed fields here\n}\n\nif allowedKeys[key] {\n    secret = status.FieldByName(key)\n} else {\n    // handle error condition here\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `allowedKeys` is a map where the keys are the names of the fields that are allowed to be accessed. Before accessing a field in the `status` object, the code checks if the `key` is in the `allowedKeys` map. If it's not, the code doesn't attempt to access the field and instead handles the error condition.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example doesn't appear to require any specific library dependencies beyond what's included in the standard Go library.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-807: Reliance on Untrusted Inputs in a Security Decision](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/807.html)\n- [CWE-470: Use of Externally-Controlled Input to Select Classes or Code ('Unsafe Reflection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/470.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-470",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/470.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-470"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6a505957-1564-3cce-89c1-e2f6a31a91a8",
              "name": "Unverified JWT Signature Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnverified JWT Signature Vulnerability is a security flaw that occurs when a JSON Web Token (JWT) is accepted without verifying its signature. This can lead to unauthorized access as an attacker can modify the token payload and use it to impersonate other users, gain unauthorized privileges, or perform other malicious activities.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the JWT token is split into its components and the payload is decoded and unmarshalled into a map without any verification of the token's signature. This leaves the application vulnerable to attacks as it trusts the token's payload without ensuring its integrity and authenticity.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always verify the JWT signature before using the token's payload. This ensures that the token was issued by a trusted source and has not been tampered with.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix using the `jwt-go` library to parse and verify the token:\n\n```go\nimport (\n\t\"github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\"\n)\n\nfunc parseToken(tokenString string) (map[string]interface{}, error) {\n\ttoken, err := jwt.Parse(tokenString, func(token *jwt.Token) (interface{}, error) {\n\t\t// Don't forget to validate the alg is what you expect:\n\t\tif _, ok := token.Method.(*jwt.SigningMethodHMAC); !ok {\n\t\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unexpected signing method: %v\", token.Header[\"alg\"])\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn []byte(\"your-256-bit-secret\"), nil\n\t})\n\n\tif claims, ok := token.Claims.(jwt.MapClaims); ok && token.Valid {\n\t\treturn claims, nil\n\t} else {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `jwt.Parse` is used to parse and verify the token. The function provided to `jwt.Parse` is used to supply the key for verification and to validate the signing method. Replace `\"your-256-bit-secret\"` with your actual secret key.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- `github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP JWT Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/JSON_Web_Token_Cheat_Sheet_for_Java.html)\n- [CWE-347: Improper Verification of Cryptographic Signature](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/347.html)"
              },
