            {
              "id": "6d1f9b68-0547-3f04-9073-5df36e7d5196",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration defaults to insecure TLS1.0, set it to a secure version like `VersionTLS13`.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `tls.Config` struct is used to configure TLS (Transport Layer Security) clients and servers. If the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` is not set, it defaults to TLS 1.0, which is considered insecure due to several known vulnerabilities. This could potentially expose the application to various attacks such as BEAST, CRIME and POODLE.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of TLS, such as `tls.VersionTLS13`.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is how you can fix the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\ntlsConfig = &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs:            caPool,\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n    ServerName:         server,\n    MinVersion:         tls.VersionTLS13,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a built-in Go library for TLS support.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "71512ab2-16c5-3c98-922d-6b050950df8b",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Password Vulnerability in Struct\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Password Vulnerability in Struct is a security flaw in Go programming language where sensitive data like username and password are hardcoded directly into the source code. This is a serious security risk as it exposes sensitive data to anyone who has access to the source code. It also makes the system vulnerable to attacks if the source code is ever leaked or compromised.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vault services to store and retrieve sensitive data. These methods provide a secure way to handle sensitive data without exposing them in the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the username and password in the struct, retrieve them from environment variables:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\ncredentials := v3.BasicLogin{\n\tUsername: os.Getenv(\"USERNAME\"),\n\tPassword: os.Getenv(\"PASSWORD\"),\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `USERNAME` and `PASSWORD` are environment variables that store the username and password. The `os.Getenv` function retrieves the values of these variables.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `os` standard library and the `v3` library where `BasicLogin` struct is defined. The exact name and version of the `v3` library cannot be determined from the provided code snippet.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-259: Use of Hard-coded Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/259.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "73dc488d-258f-3f41-b02c-c340ace9f724",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data such as credentials are hardcoded into the program, as shown in the example:\n\n```go\nrancherCredentialsFolder = \"/cattle-credentials\"\n```\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure storage mechanisms to store and retrieve sensitive data. \n\nEnsure that sensitive data is encrypted both at rest and in transit. Use strong, industry-standard cryptographic algorithms and keep cryptographic keys secure.\n\nImplement proper access controls and permissions to limit who can access sensitive data. Regularly review and update these controls as necessary.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the credentials folder, you can use an environment variable to store the path. This way, the path can be changed without modifying the source code, and it is not exposed in the source code:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nrancherCredentialsFolder := os.Getenv(\"RANCHER_CREDENTIALS_FOLDER\")\n```\n\nIn this example, `RANCHER_CREDENTIALS_FOLDER` is an environment variable that stores the path to the credentials folder. You can set this environment variable in your system or in your application's runtime environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `os` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "74746e51-2468-36be-8b49-067ae23845a8",
              "name": "Storing Sensitive Information as Hardcoded Constants Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nStoring sensitive information as hardcoded constants is a common vulnerability in many programming languages, including Go. This vulnerability occurs when sensitive data such as passwords, API keys, or cryptographic key material are embedded directly into the source code. This is a bad practice because it exposes the sensitive data to anyone who has access to the source code, and it makes it difficult to change the sensitive data without modifying and redeploying the application.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the string \"RKESecretsMigrated\" is hardcoded as a constant. If this string is a sensitive piece of information (like a password or a secret key), then this would be a vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nSensitive data should never be hardcoded into the application. Instead, it should be stored in a secure manner and retrieved as needed. This could be done using environment variables, secure configuration files, or secure storage services, depending on the specific needs of the application.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIf \"RKESecretsMigrated\" is a sensitive piece of information, it should not be hardcoded. Instead, it could be stored in an environment variable and retrieved as needed. Here is an example of how to do this in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    condition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"RKESecretsMigrated\")\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the sensitive data is stored in an environment variable named \"RKESecretsMigrated\". The `os.Getenv` function is used to retrieve the value of the environment variable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "74b0a96e-c68d-3299-8184-26b39cb15245",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7638f3eb-5ab3-3e62-84b8-426d51f19a85",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. In the context of Go programming language, unescaped user-controlled data in HTTP response can lead to XSS vulnerabilities. If an application uses unsanitized user input in HTTP responses without proper encoding, an attacker can inject malicious scripts that will be executed in the browser of any user viewing the manipulated page.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always encode user-controlled data that is included in HTTP responses. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically handles escaping. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the user-controlled data to the HTTP response, you should use the `html/template` package to safely encode the data. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"foo\").Parse(`{{.}}`)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(res, js)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `js` is the user-controlled data. The `template` package automatically escapes the data when executing the template.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "76f44ffe-5fa2-31bd-83a1-8046a487826d",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data like passwords, API keys, or secrets are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this information. These methods allow you to change the credentials without modifying the code and also keep the credentials out of the source code repository.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly into the source code, you can use an environment variable to store the secret. Here is how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    ClusterPrivateRegistrySecret := os.Getenv(\"PrivateRegistrySecret\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `PrivateRegistrySecret` is an environment variable that stores the secret. You can set the environment variable in your operating system or in the configuration of your application.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `os` package which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7e141b25-96e9-3940-84ad-e0109618e803",
              "name": "\"MD5's Cryptographic Vulnerability: Use bcrypt, argon2id, SHA-256, or SHA-3 Instead\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nMD5 is a widely used cryptographic hash function that produces a 128-bit (16-byte) hash value. It is commonly used to verify data integrity. However, MD5 is not collision-resistant; as of 2020, researchers can generate different inputs that hash to the same MD5 hash. This vulnerability can be exploited by attackers to create malicious data with the same hash as legitimate data, leading to potential security risks such as data integrity violation and unauthorized information disclosure.\n\nIn Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 hash. The `Sum` function in this package returns the MD5 checksum of the data.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, use a more secure hash function such as bcrypt, argon2id, SHA-256, or SHA-3. These hash functions are more resistant to collision attacks.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nReplace the `crypto/md5` package with a more secure hash function. Here is an example of how to use the `crypto/sha256` package to compute the SHA-256 hash:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"fmt\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    data := []byte(\"your data\")\n    sum := sha256.Sum256(data)\n    fmt.Printf(\"SHA-256 hash: %x\\n\", sum)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `fmt`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-328",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-328"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7e206b06-1dee-321a-8062-59f2d73a114e",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common mistake that developers make, especially when they are under pressure to deliver quickly. The problem with this approach is that anyone who has access to the source code can easily extract these secrets and use them for malicious purposes.\n\nIn the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if developers hardcode sensitive data directly into their Go source code. This can be particularly dangerous if the source code is publicly accessible, such as in an open source project.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to avoid hardcoding sensitive data into your source code. Instead, you should store these secrets in a secure and encrypted manner, and retrieve them through a secure method at runtime. This could be done using environment variables, secure configuration files, or secure secret management systems.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is not clear as there are no hardcoded credentials or API keys in the provided code snippet. However, if there were, the fix would involve removing the hardcoded secrets and replacing them with secure methods of retrieving these secrets at runtime.\n\nFor example, if there was a hardcoded API key in the code, it could be replaced with an environment variable like this:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    apiKey := os.Getenv(\"API_KEY\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the API key is stored as an environment variable named \"API_KEY\", and it is retrieved at runtime using the `os.Getenv` function.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - 2017: A3-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7e983b87-02c9-338f-b2b1-7870ba3458e8",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal a user's session cookie and impersonate them.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `false`. This means that the cookie can be transmitted over unsecured HTTP connections, which can be intercepted by attackers.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only transmitted over secure HTTPS connections. Additionally, consider setting the `HttpOnly` attribute to `true` to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, which can help prevent cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     cookieName,\n\tValue:    \"\",\n\tSecure:   true, // Set Secure to true\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tMaxAge:   -1,\n\tExpires:  cookieUnsetTimestamp,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "80fc0f72-351f-333f-b755-613476020cc9",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its cookies, which could allow an attacker to intercept and manipulate the cookies, potentially leading to session hijacking or identity theft. In the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `false` or not set at all, which means the cookie can be transmitted over unencrypted connections.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which is an encrypted connection. Additionally, consider using the `HttpOnly` attribute to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, which can help prevent cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\npkceCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     pkceVerifierCookieName,\n\tValue:    \"\",\n\tSecure:   true, // Always use secure cookies\n\tHttpOnly: true, // Prevent access from client-side script\n\tExpires:  time.Now().Add(time.Second * -10),\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: for the `http.Cookie` struct\n- `time`: for the `time.Now` function and `time.Second` constant\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "80ff1594-9fb0-3a93-8086-590702041748",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration leading to insecure default value TLS1.0",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Go programming language's `tls.Config` struct allows for the configuration of TLS clients and servers. If the `MinVersion` field is not set, the default minimum version of TLS that will be negotiated is TLS 1.0. This version of TLS is considered insecure and deprecated, and its use can expose the application to various attacks, such as BEAST, CRIME, and POODLE.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of TLS. As of the time of writing, the recommended minimum version is TLS 1.2.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can set the `MinVersion` field in your `tls.Config`:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\n// ...\n\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs:      pool,\n    Certificates: certs,\n    MinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS12,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
