            {
              "id": "8546d15d-c5ee-38aa-85dc-14bf7e5ebcc7",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or secrets are hardcoded into the application's source code. This is a serious issue because if the source code is exposed or leaked, an attacker can easily extract these credentials and use them to gain unauthorized access to systems or services.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data is hardcoded into the code, as shown in the following example:\n\n```go\nAuthConfigConditionShibbolethSecretFixed condition.Cond = \"ShibbolethSecretFixed\"\n```\n\nIn this case, the secret for the Shibboleth authentication is hardcoded into the code, which is a security risk.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding sensitive data into your application's source code. Instead, use secure methods to store and retrieve these data, such as environment variables, secure configuration files, or secure storage services.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the specific vulnerability sink in the code example:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nAuthConfigConditionShibbolethSecretFixed condition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"SHIBBOLETH_SECRET\")\n```\n\nIn this fix, the secret is retrieved from an environment variable named `SHIBBOLETH_SECRET` instead of being hardcoded into the code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not provide enough context to determine the specific library dependencies required for it to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "89d3c38f-efb8-3764-8815-258a31edcfd6",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common issue in many programming languages, including Go. \n\nHardcoding sensitive information in the source code is a bad practice because it exposes the data to anyone who has access to the source code. This could include other developers, version control systems, or even attackers if the source code is publicly accessible. \n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `ClusterTemplateRevisionConditionSecretsMigrated` variable is assigned a hardcoded value of `\"SecretsMigrated\"`. If this value is a sensitive secret, it could be exposed to unauthorized users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, sensitive data should never be hardcoded into the source code. Instead, it should be stored in a secure manner and accessed through secure means. This could include using environment variables, secure configuration files, or secure secret management systems.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret into the source code, you could store it in an environment variable and access it using the `os` package in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    ClusterTemplateRevisionConditionSecretsMigrated := os.Getenv(\"SECRETS_MIGRATED\")\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the secret is stored in the `SECRETS_MIGRATED` environment variable and accessed securely through the `os.Getenv` function.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A3-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8f29bcc2-01cc-3cfd-81b3-b918d39f428b",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data like passwords, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded directly into the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive data. These methods allow you to separate your credentials from your source code, making it harder for an attacker to gain access to them.\n\nEnsure that your environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults are properly secured and not accessible to unauthorized users. Regularly rotate your credentials and use strong, unique passwords.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nAssuming the hardcoded credential is in the `ClusterTemplateRevisionConditionRKESecretsMigrated` condition, you can replace it with an environment variable. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    // Get the secret from an environment variable\n    secret := os.Getenv(\"RKE_SECRETS_MIGRATED\")\n\n    ClusterTemplateRevisionConditionRKESecretsMigrated condition.Cond = secret\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the secret is stored in the `RKE_SECRETS_MIGRATED` environment variable. You can set this environment variable in your server or deployment configuration.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "90d44c6a-da69-3dfb-859f-4c0a26625f1e",
              "name": "Public Accessibility of Profiling Endpoints Due to Import of net/http/pprof Package",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `net/http/pprof` package in Go programming language is used for profiling and debugging. When imported, it automatically registers its HTTP handlers with the default HTTP Mux. This means that if your application is running an HTTP server using the default HTTP Mux, the profiling endpoints will be publicly accessible, which can lead to information disclosure and potential misuse.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid importing the `net/http/pprof` package in production code. If profiling is required, it should be controlled by a build flag or configuration setting so that it can be turned off in a production environment. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of importing `net/http/pprof` in the global scope, you can import it in a restricted scope where you can control the access. Here is an example:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"log\"\n\t\"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\t// Create a new serve mux\n\tmux := http.NewServeMux()\n\n\t// Register pprof handlers\n\tif isDebugMode() {\n\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"/debug/pprof/\", pprof.Index)\n\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"/debug/pprof/cmdline\", pprof.Cmdline)\n\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"/debug/pprof/profile\", pprof.Profile)\n\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"/debug/pprof/symbol\", pprof.Symbol)\n\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"/debug/pprof/trace\", pprof.Trace)\n\t}\n\n\tlog.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(\":8080\", mux))\n}\n\nfunc isDebugMode() bool {\n\t// return true if in debug mode\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the pprof handlers are only registered if the application is in debug mode.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `log`\n- `net/http`\n- `net/http/pprof`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10-2017 A3-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "92c19204-f1a0-3470-851c-a5ad5380d249",
              "name": "InsecureSkipVerify: true disables TLS certificate validation, exposing connection to man-in-the-middle attacks.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, setting `InsecureSkipVerify: true` in the `tls.Config` struct disables the TLS (Transport Layer Security) certificate validation. This is a security vulnerability as it exposes the connection to man-in-the-middle (MITM) attacks. In a MITM attack, the attacker secretly relays and possibly alters the communication between two parties who believe they are directly communicating with each other.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always validate TLS certificates. This can be done by setting `InsecureSkipVerify: false` in the `tls.Config` struct. This ensures that the client verifies the server's certificate against the available CA certificates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the recommended fix for the vulnerability:\n\n```go\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This package implements the TLS protocol, which provides communication security over the internet.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-295: Improper Certificate Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-295",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-295"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "97341169-8ea3-38ed-a502-96abb6d1b044",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly within the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data like API keys, passwords, or secret keys are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vault services to store and access these credentials. These methods allow you to separate your credentials from your source code, making it harder for an attacker to gain unauthorized access.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nvar IdentityTokenAuthConfigSecretKey string\n\nfunc init() {\n    IdentityTokenAuthConfigSecretKey = os.Getenv(\"IDENTITY_TOKEN_SECRET_KEY\")\n    if IdentityTokenAuthConfigSecretKey == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"IDENTITY_TOKEN_SECRET_KEY must be set\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `IDENTITY_TOKEN_SECRET_KEY` environment variable is used to store the secret key. The `os.Getenv` function is used to retrieve the value of the environment variable. If the environment variable is not set, the program will log a fatal error and exit.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `os` package from the Go standard library\n- The `log` package from the Go standard library\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9ae67331-387a-3d08-88b4-381baa78b812",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data such as access tokens, API keys, or passwords are hardcoded into the program.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this information. These methods allow you to change the credentials without modifying the code and provide better security measures to protect the data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the access token secret name, you can use an environment variable to store this information. Here is an example of how you can do this in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    AccessTokenSecretName := os.Getenv(\"AZUREAD_ACCESS_TOKEN\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `os.Getenv` is a function that retrieves the value of the environment variable named `AZUREAD_ACCESS_TOKEN`. You can set this environment variable in your operating system or in the configuration of your application.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9b8ccde7-7267-3538-b438-eb9b5710f43c",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable\" is a vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, cryptographic keys, or other secrets are hardcoded directly into the source code. This is a common issue in Go programming language when developers store such sensitive data in package-level variables. This practice is insecure as it exposes the sensitive data to anyone who has access to the source code, and it also makes the data difficult to change without modifying and redeploying the code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use secure methods to store and retrieve these data, such as environment variables, secure configuration files, or secure key stores. \n\nEnsure that sensitive data is properly protected in transit and at rest. Use encryption and secure protocols to protect data in transit, and use secure methods to store data at rest.\n\nLimit access to sensitive data to only those components of the application that require it. Use the principle of least privilege to minimize the potential damage if a component is compromised.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the credential in the package-level variable, you can store it in an environment variable and retrieve it when needed. Here is how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nvar NamespacedDockerCredentialResourceName string\n\nfunc init() {\n    NamespacedDockerCredentialResourceName = os.Getenv(\"NAMESPACED_DOCKER_CREDENTIAL\")\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `NAMESPACED_DOCKER_CREDENTIAL` environment variable is used to store the credential. The `init` function retrieves the value of this environment variable and assigns it to the `NamespacedDockerCredentialResourceName` variable when the package is initialized.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the built-in `os` package in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a4be31c8-dcdb-321a-a73d-b20818f6b65f",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a63dde47-82dc-3362-a916-51324a153226",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common issue in many programming languages, including Go. If an attacker gains access to the source code, they can easily extract these secrets and use them to gain unauthorized access to systems or data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this data. These methods allow you to change the secrets without modifying the code and can provide additional layers of security.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secrets into your code, you can use the `os` package in Go to read environment variables. Here is an example:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\tapiKey := os.Getenv(\"API_KEY\")\n\tif apiKey == \"\" {\n\t\tfmt.Println(\"missing API_KEY\")\n\t\tos.Exit(1)\n\t}\n\n\t// use apiKey\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `API_KEY` environment variable is used to store the API key. If the environment variable is not set, the program will exit with an error message.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the standard `os` and `fmt` packages provided by Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A3 - Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a7fc29ab-af19-371d-88f9-a370af5fc4a9",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or secrets are hardcoded into the application's source code. This is a serious issue because if the source code is exposed or accessible, an attacker can easily extract these credentials and misuse them.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when developers hardcode sensitive data directly into the source code. For example, the following line of code is a vulnerability sink:\n\n```go\nAccessTokenSecretName = \"azuread-access-token\"\n```\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive data. These methods allow you to change the data without modifying the code and also keep the data out of the source code, reducing the risk of exposure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly into the source code, you can use an environment variable to store the secret. Here is how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    AccessTokenSecretName := os.Getenv(\"AZUREAD_ACCESS_TOKEN\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv(\"AZUREAD_ACCESS_TOKEN\")` retrieves the value of the `AZUREAD_ACCESS_TOKEN` environment variable. You can set this environment variable in your server or development environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A3 - Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ab1cf3da-aa5d-3962-a5da-e1860f3384a2",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` attribute of the cookie is set to the value of `isSecure` variable. If `isSecure` is false, the cookie will be transmitted over unsecured HTTP connections, which makes it vulnerable to interception and tampering.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of cookies to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which encrypts the data and prevents it from being intercepted or tampered with.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\npkceCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     pkceVerifierCookieName,\n\tValue:    value,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tExpires:  time.Now().Add(time.Minute * 10),\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: for creating and managing HTTP requests and responses, including cookies.\n- `time`: for setting the expiration time of the cookie.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ad4e04d5-83ec-3003-b63e-932663946f03",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as passwords, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the application's source code. This is a common issue in many programming languages, including Go. If an attacker gains access to the source code, they can easily extract these secrets and use them to gain unauthorized access to systems or data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this data. These methods allow you to change the secrets without modifying the source code and can provide additional layers of security.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key in your Go code:\n\n```go\nPasswordAuthConfigSecretKey = \"password\"\n```\n\nYou can use an environment variable to store the secret key:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nPasswordAuthConfigSecretKey = os.Getenv(\"PASSWORD_AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_KEY\")\n```\n\nIn this case, you need to set the `PASSWORD_AUTH_CONFIG_SECRET_KEY` environment variable to the secret key value before running your Go application.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe Go standard library `os` is required by the code example to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ad693884-8a32-3c25-ba55-b554ef47e2eb",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the practice of embedding sensitive information such as credentials, cryptographic keys, and other secrets directly into the source code. This is a security risk as it exposes these secrets to anyone who has access to the source code. In the provided code snippet, the variable `ClusterAuthTokenResourceName` is hardcoded, which could potentially be a security vulnerability if it contains sensitive information.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information in your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vault services to store and access these secrets. These methods allow you to separate your secrets from your source code, reducing the risk of exposure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the `ClusterAuthTokenResourceName` in your source code, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nvar ClusterAuthTokenResourceName string\n\nfunc init() {\n    ClusterAuthTokenResourceName = os.Getenv(\"CLUSTER_AUTH_TOKEN_RESOURCE_NAME\")\n    if ClusterAuthTokenResourceName == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"CLUSTER_AUTH_TOKEN_RESOURCE_NAME not set\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `ClusterAuthTokenResourceName` is retrieved from the environment variable `CLUSTER_AUTH_TOKEN_RESOURCE_NAME` when the package is initialized. If the environment variable is not set, the program will log a fatal error and exit.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Security Credentials](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b1a480ab-2d4f-3c26-a045-9022c9a1cd73",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b290704c-889b-365b-8a3a-a10e2ecead95",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common issue in many programming languages, including Go. If an attacker gains access to the source code, they can easily extract these secrets and use them for malicious purposes.\n\nIn the provided Go code snippet, the vulnerability sink is the hardcoded string \"ACISecretsMigrated\". If this string is used as a secret key or credential, it could be easily discovered by an attacker.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store and retrieve these secrets. These methods make it more difficult for an attacker to discover your secrets, even if they gain access to your source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly into the code, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can modify the provided code snippet to use an environment variable:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// ...\n\ncondition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"ACI_SECRETS_MIGRATED\")\n```\n\nIn this modified code, the secret is stored in an environment variable named \"ACI_SECRETS_MIGRATED\". You can set the value of this environment variable in your system or in your application's runtime environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP: Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b44e32b4-173c-3af1-bacc-8553d51fcd35",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data like application secret keys are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store and access these credentials. Ensure that these storage mechanisms are properly secured with appropriate permissions and encryption.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key in the source code, you can use an environment variable to store the secret key. Here is how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    appSecretKey := os.Getenv(\"APP_SECRET_KEY\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `APP_SECRET_KEY` is an environment variable that stores the application secret key. You can set the value of this environment variable in your server or local development environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `os` package which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b7e3265b-9ade-30dc-9ad7-c61e07d95255",
              "name": "\"MD5's Cryptographic Vulnerability: Inappropriate for Security-Sensitive Uses; Use bcrypt, argon2id, SHA-256, or SHA-3 Instead\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hashing algorithm is considered cryptographically broken and unsuitable for further use. Its main weakness is that it's vulnerable to hash collisions, where different inputs produce the same hash output. This makes it inappropriate for functions such as SSL certificates or encryption that require a unique and secure hash. \n\nIn the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 checksum (a widely used cryptographic hash function) of a data. However, due to the vulnerabilities associated with MD5, it's not recommended for security-sensitive uses.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nFor security-sensitive uses, consider using stronger hash functions such as bcrypt, argon2id, SHA-256, or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered to be much more secure and resistant to hash collisions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of MD5 with a more secure hash function. Here's an example of how to use SHA-256 instead:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `crypto/sha256` package is used to compute the SHA-256 checksum. The `encoding/hex` package is used to convert the checksum to a hexadecimal string.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-328",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-328"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b9775810-4208-34b1-afda-78d05f470ad2",
              "name": "\"Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic uses because it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to substitute a malicious input for a legitimate one without detection. In the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 checksum (a type of hash function) of data.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `md5.Sum` function is used to generate a unique identifier based on the current time. This could potentially be exploited if an attacker is able to predict or control the time value used as input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a more secure hash algorithm such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure against collision attacks and are suitable for most cryptographic uses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `md5.Sum` with `sha256.Sum256` or `sha3.Sum256` from the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` packages respectively. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go standard library packages:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ba980308-8542-355c-ad56-5b1b96d7f49c",
              "name": "\"Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic uses because it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to substitute a malicious input for a legitimate one without detection. In the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 checksum (a type of hash function) of data.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `md5.Sum` function is used to generate a unique identifier based on the current time. This could potentially be exploited if an attacker is able to predict or control the time value used as input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a more secure hash algorithm such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure against collision attacks and are suitable for most cryptographic uses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `md5.Sum` with `sha256.Sum256` or `sha3.Sum256` from the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` packages respectively. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go standard library packages:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "bfb236b1-e9f3-31bc-9cb4-8dc7efeb2489",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed, as the credentials are easily readable. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data like password hashes are hardcoded into the program.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use secure methods of storing and retrieving credentials, such as environment variables, configuration files, or secure vault services. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the password hash annotation, you can retrieve it from an environment variable. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\npasswordHashAnnotation := os.Getenv(\"PASSWORD_HASH\")\n```\n\nIn this case, `PASSWORD_HASH` is an environment variable that stores the password hash. You can set this environment variable in your server or local machine where the Go program runs.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `os` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
