            {
              "id": "c2d1c8fe-6685-30e1-834e-bc0bd7a43bc7",
              "name": "Unintended Public Server Exposure due to Binding to All Interfaces",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the vulnerability \"Unintended Public Server Exposure due to Binding to All Interfaces\" occurs when a network service is unintentionally exposed to the public internet. This happens when the service binds to all network interfaces (0.0.0.0 or ::), instead of binding to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1). This can lead to unauthorized access to the service, data leakage, or even remote code execution.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `net.Listen(\"tcp\", \":0\")` function call binds the listener to all network interfaces, which can expose the server to the public internet.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should bind your service to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1) unless it is necessary for the service to be accessible from the public internet. This will ensure that the service is only accessible from the local machine.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nlistener, err := net.Listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:0\") // bind to localhost and choose any available port\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet only requires the `net` package from the standard library of Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-284: Improper Access Control](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/284.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c43e625e-e4c1-3e40-b3c3-b4abe582faa4",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c4d9a10d-f192-3b54-9d00-5ab80501450a",
              "name": "\"Redirect Target Vulnerability from Untrusted Request Data\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Redirect Target Vulnerability from Untrusted Request Data\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when an application uses input from an HTTP request to directly determine the location to which it should redirect the user. This can allow an attacker to craft a URL that, if clicked, may redirect a user from the intended application to an arbitrary domain of the attacker's choosing. This can lead to various attacks such as phishing and stealing of user credentials.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Redirect` function is used with untrusted input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user input to determine the redirect target without validation. If user input must be used, ensure that it is validated and sanitized before use. This can be done by checking that the URL is in a list of trusted URLs or by using a method that ensures the URL is safe.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the vulnerability. In this example, we assume that `trustedURLs` is a list of trusted URLs.\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"net/url\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, req *http.Request) {\n    redirectURL := req.URL.Query().Get(\"redirectURL\")\n    parsedURL, err := url.Parse(redirectURL)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, \"Invalid URL\", http.StatusBadRequest)\n        return\n    }\n\n    for _, trustedURL := range trustedURLs {\n        if parsedURL.Host == trustedURL {\n            http.Redirect(w, req, redirectURL, http.StatusFound)\n            return\n        }\n    }\n\n    http.Error(w, \"Untrusted redirect target\", http.StatusBadRequest)\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we parse the URL from the user input and check if the host of the URL is in the list of trusted URLs. If it is, we proceed with the redirection. If it is not, we return an error.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following standard library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `net/url`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-601"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c6a5d5cf-ed8d-3373-b86b-84d75ed84bf2",
              "name": "\"Possible Denial-of-Service Detection via Zip Bomb Attack: Mitigation Using `io.CopyN()`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Go programming language has a vulnerability that can lead to a Denial-of-Service (DoS) attack via a Zip Bomb. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it, because its actual size far exceeds the declared size in the archive metadata. \n\nThe vulnerability lies in the `io.Copy()` function, which is used to copy data from a source to a destination. If the source is a Zip Bomb, the function will continue to read data until the source is exhausted, potentially consuming all available system resources and causing a DoS condition.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you can use the `io.CopyN()` function instead of `io.Copy()`. The `io.CopyN()` function copies a specified number of bytes (N) from the source to the destination. By limiting the amount of data that can be read from the source, you can prevent a Zip Bomb from consuming all system resources.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is an example of how to use `io.CopyN()` to mitigate this vulnerability:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    src, _ := os.Open(\"source.zip\")\n    dst, _ := os.Create(\"destination.zip\")\n    _, err := io.CopyN(dst, src, 1024*1024) // copy only 1MB of data\n    if err != nil {\n        // handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, only 1MB of data is copied from the source to the destination. If the source is a Zip Bomb, it will not be able to consume more than 1MB of system resources.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption ('Resource Exhaustion')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c8d8fce6-204c-3f14-8f0d-c09cfdf4c365",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed or the credentials are discovered. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data like usernames, passwords, or secret keys are hardcoded into the program.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials into your code. Instead, use environment variables, external configuration files, or secure vault systems to store sensitive information. This way, even if your source code is exposed, your credentials remain secure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key into your program, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    secretKey := os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")\n    if secretKey == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"SECRET_KEY is required\")\n    }\n    // Use secretKey\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `SECRET_KEY` is an environment variable that stores your secret key. You can set this environment variable in your operating system, or directly in your Go program before you run it.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c9b82af0-be87-367f-ab10-83dc29209f83",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as passwords, API keys, or other credentials are hardcoded directly into the source code. This is a common issue in Go programming language when developers store credentials in package-level variables. This practice is insecure because it exposes sensitive data to anyone who has access to the source code. It also makes it difficult to change the credentials without modifying and redeploying the code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store credentials. These methods allow you to change the credentials without modifying the code, and they can be secured to limit who has access to the credentials.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the password into the source code, you can use an environment variable to store the password. Here is how you can modify the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nvar DummyPassword string\n\nfunc init() {\n    DummyPassword = os.Getenv(\"DUMMY_PASSWORD\")\n    if DummyPassword == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"DUMMY_PASSWORD environment variable is not set\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the password is read from the `DUMMY_PASSWORD` environment variable when the program starts. If the environment variable is not set, the program will log a fatal error and exit.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the standard `os` and `log` packages from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Password](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cbd612e0-dd11-3c02-8a98-2c84a909ad43",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data like API keys, database credentials, or other secrets are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials in your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store sensitive information. These methods allow you to separate your credentials from your source code, making it harder for an attacker to gain access to them.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is not related to hardcoded credentials. However, if it were, a potential fix could look like this:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    condition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"SECRETS_MIGRATED\")\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the secret is stored in an environment variable named `SECRETS_MIGRATED` instead of being hardcoded into the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not indicate any specific library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
