            {
              "id": "cbebdbfd-a3f5-3223-9518-23165b592709",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure through Hardcoded Credentials or API Keys is a security vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as usernames, passwords, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded into the source code. This is a common issue in Go programming language as well as other languages. The problem arises when this code is exposed to the public, for example, through open source repositories, or if an attacker gains access to the source code. This can lead to unauthorized access to systems or data, data breaches, and other security incidents.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to avoid hardcoding sensitive data in the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this data. These methods allow you to change the data without changing the code and keep the data out of the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key in the source code, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here is how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    secretKey := os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")\n    if secretKey == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"SECRET_KEY is required\")\n    }\n    // Use secretKey\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")` retrieves the value of the `SECRET_KEY` environment variable. If the variable is not set, the program will log a fatal error and exit.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It uses only the standard library provided by Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A3 - Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cd49ff58-2366-3cb6-b6b1-388706942a71",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. In the context of Go programming language, the vulnerability \"Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\" refers to the situation where user-controlled data is directly written to HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding. This can lead to a potential XSS attack if an attacker is able to control the data that is being written to the HTTP response.\n\nIn the provided code snippet `rw.Write([]byte(err.Error()))`, the error message, which could potentially be controlled by the user, is written directly to the HTTP response without any sanitization or encoding.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and/or encode user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically handles the encoding of user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(err.Error())\nt.Execute(rw, nil)\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, the error message is treated as a template string and is automatically HTML-encoded by the `template.Execute` method before being written to the HTTP response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code example requires the following library dependency:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go and does not need to be separately installed.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d57c479b-dc7a-3ccb-804f-f3b3282378f0",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d85276cb-322b-3679-a468-047ff8126ece",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Cookie` struct is used to create a cookie without the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields set to `true`. The `Secure` field ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted in transit. The `HttpOnly` field prevents the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, mitigating the risk of cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields to `true` when creating a cookie. Additionally, consider using the `SameSite` field to further protect against cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nr.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n    Name:     \"R_OIDC_ID\",\n    Value:    \"test-id-token\",\n    Secure:   true,\n    HttpOnly: true,\n    SameSite: http.SameSiteStrictMode,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `net/http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Secure Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [OWASP - SameSite Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#samesite-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dae76469-d76c-3078-a41b-cbfbf7a8e794",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed or if the credentials are not properly secured. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data such as passwords, API keys, or other secrets are hardcoded directly into the source code.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the string \"ACISecretsMigrated\" is hardcoded into the condition.Cond variable. If this string is a sensitive credential, it could be exploited if the source code is exposed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store and access these credentials. These methods allow for easier management and rotation of credentials, and they keep the credentials out of the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the string directly into the source code, you could use an environment variable to store the credential. Here's how you could modify the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// ...\n\nClusterTemplateRevisionConditionACISecretsMigrated condition.Cond = os.Getenv(\"ACI_SECRETS_MIGRATED\")\n```\n\nIn this example, \"ACI_SECRETS_MIGRATED\" is an environment variable that stores the credential. This way, the credential is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the required library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
