            {
              "id": "defb9758-08d8-3860-a17a-662faafa95b3",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed, as the credentials are easily readable. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when sensitive data like application secrets, API keys, or passwords are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store this information. These methods allow you to change the credentials without modifying the code and also keep the credentials out of the source code repository.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret value, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    appSecretValue := os.Getenv(\"APP_SECRET_VALUE\")\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `APP_SECRET_VALUE` is an environment variable that stores the secret value. You can set this environment variable in your server or local machine where the application is running.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `os` package which is part of the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e1bc250c-76ea-3717-9ffc-81e9738bf6e6",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable\" is a vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials, cryptographic keys, or other secrets are hardcoded directly into the source code. This is a common mistake that can lead to serious security issues. In the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when a package-level variable is used to store such sensitive data.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the variable `cleanedUpSecretsAnnotation` is declared as a constant at the package level. If this variable was used to store sensitive data, it would be a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into your source code. Instead, use secure methods of storing and retrieving these data, such as environment variables, secure configuration files, or secure key stores.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret into the source code, you can use environment variables to store the secret. Here is an example of how you can do this in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nvar cleanedUpSecretsAnnotation = os.Getenv(\"CLEANED_UP_SECRETS_ANNOTATION\")\n```\n\nIn this example, the secret is stored in an environment variable named `CLEANED_UP_SECRETS_ANNOTATION`. This way, the secret is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A2: Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e4da3941-337a-3704-a679-7691a8685f9b",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Cookie` struct is used to create a cookie without the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields set to `true`. The `Secure` field ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted in transit. The `HttpOnly` field prevents the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, mitigating the risk of cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields to `true` when creating a cookie. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over secure connections and cannot be accessed through client-side scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nr.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n\tName:     tokens.CookieName,\n\tValue:    bearerToken,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Secure Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly Flag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e651012e-812f-3462-8028-5c63d3cc02ab",
              "name": "Public Accessibility of Profiling Endpoints Due to Import of net/http/pprof Package",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `net/http/pprof` package is used to serve via HTTP a view of the profiling data collected in a program. When this package is imported, it registers its profiling endpoints with the default HTTP server provided by the `net/http` package. If the program also starts this default server, for example by calling `http.ListenAndServe`, then these profiling endpoints become publicly accessible over the network. This can lead to information disclosure as an attacker can access sensitive profiling data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid importing the `net/http/pprof` package in production code. If profiling is required, it should be controlled by a build flag or configuration setting so that it can be turned off in a production environment. Additionally, access to the profiling endpoints should be restricted, for example by using authentication or by only allowing access from certain IP addresses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to conditionally import the `net/http/pprof` package based on a build flag:\n\n```go\n// +build debug\n\nimport (\n\t_ \"net/http/pprof\"\n)\n```\n\nWith this code, the `net/http/pprof` package will only be imported if the program is built with the `-tags debug` flag.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `log`\n- `net/http`\n- `net/http/pprof`\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e9721798-b723-3942-8902-0feaa9e565b2",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `false` or not set at all. The `Secure` attribute ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted by an attacker.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over secure connections. Additionally, consider setting the `HttpOnly` attribute to `true` to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, further reducing the risk of session hijacking.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     IDTokenCookie,\n\tValue:    token,\n\tSecure:   true, // Always set Secure to true\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `http` package, which is part of the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f0916143-df0c-37c9-8b03-29cbfb566bd4",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Hardcoded Credential Stored in Package-Level Variable\" is a vulnerability that occurs when sensitive data such as credentials are hardcoded directly into the source code. This is a security risk as it exposes sensitive data to anyone who has access to the source code. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when credentials are stored in package-level variables.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to avoid hardcoding sensitive data directly into the source code. Instead, use secure methods to store and retrieve sensitive data such as:\n\n- Environment variables\n- Secure configuration files\n- Secure databases\n- Secure vault services\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the credential into the package-level variable, you can store it in an environment variable and retrieve it when needed. Here is how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nvar DockerCredentialResourceName string\n\nfunc init() {\n    DockerCredentialResourceName = os.Getenv(\"DOCKER_CREDENTIAL_RESOURCE_NAME\")\n    if DockerCredentialResourceName == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"DOCKER_CREDENTIAL_RESOURCE_NAME not set\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `DOCKER_CREDENTIAL_RESOURCE_NAME` environment variable is used to store the credential. The `os.Getenv` function is used to retrieve the value of the environment variable. If the environment variable is not set, the program will log a fatal error and exit.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the standard `os` and `log` packages provided by Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f333e2e4-1c5a-3988-bdfe-1ef6fc3969c4",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of embedding account credentials directly into the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access to the system if the source code is exposed or if the hardcoded credentials are discovered.\n\nIn the context of Go programming language, if the credentials are hardcoded as in the following line:\n\n`AuthConfigConditionShibbolethSecretFixed condition.Cond = \"ShibbolethSecretFixed\"`\n\nThis means that the same secret is used every time the code runs, which can be a potential security risk.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding credentials in your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or key management systems to store sensitive information. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    secret := os.Getenv(\"SHIBBOLETH_SECRET\")\n    AuthConfigConditionShibbolethSecretFixed condition.Cond = secret\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `SHIBBOLETH_SECRET` is an environment variable that stores the secret. You can set this environment variable in your server or local development environment.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not provide enough context to determine the library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f34b6fbd-6f65-3510-be79-96a5a02e3757",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly within the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed, as the credentials are easily readable. In the context of Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur if sensitive data like API keys, database credentials, or in this case, an Okta password, are hardcoded in the source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly in the source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vaults to store and access these credentials. These methods allow the credentials to be changed without modifying the code and also keep them out of the source code repository.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the Okta password, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// Get the Okta password from an environment variable\noktaPassword := os.Getenv(\"OKTA_PASSWORD\")\n\n// Use the password in the condition\nAuthConfigOKTAPasswordMigrated condition.Cond = oktaPassword\n```\n\nIn this code, the `os.Getenv` function is used to get the value of the `OKTA_PASSWORD` environment variable. This value is then used in the condition.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Credentials](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-passwords)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
