                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f4ef7957-5e58-3c79-9bb2-f5efee74b173",
              "name": "Insecure Default TLS Version Due to Missing `MinVersion` Configuration",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `Insecure Default TLS Version Due to Missing MinVersion Configuration` vulnerability arises when the `MinVersion` field in the `tls.Config` struct is not set. This field controls the minimum version of the TLS protocol that will be negotiated. If this field is not set, the Go TLS library will default to TLS 1.0, which is considered insecure due to known vulnerabilities.\n\nThe provided code snippet is vulnerable because it does not set the `MinVersion` field, and it also sets `InsecureSkipVerify` to `true`, which disables SSL certificate verification.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should:\n\n1. Set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of the TLS protocol. As of the time of writing, TLS 1.2 and 1.3 are considered secure.\n\n2. Do not set `InsecureSkipVerify` to `true`. This disables SSL certificate verification, which can lead to man-in-the-middle attacks.\n\n## Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12,\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f75097ef-42fb-3cde-a87e-dda1ac036932",
              "name": "\"Detected Session Cookie Lacks 'HttpOnly' Flag\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Detected Session Cookie Lacks 'HttpOnly' Flag\" vulnerability refers to a situation where a session cookie does not have the 'HttpOnly' flag set. This can potentially expose the cookie to cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks, as the flag is meant to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts. In Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when creating a cookie without setting the 'HttpOnly' flag to true.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always set the 'HttpOnly' flag to true when creating a cookie. This will prevent the cookie from being accessed via client-side scripts, thus reducing the risk of XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nr.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n\tName:     tokens.CookieName,\n\tValue:    bearerToken,\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n})\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, the 'HttpOnly' flag is set to true when creating the cookie.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not appear to require any specific library dependencies beyond the standard Go libraries.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP HttpOnly](https://owasp.org/www-community/HttpOnly)\n- [CWE-1004: Sensitive Cookie Without 'HttpOnly' Flag](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1004.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1004",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1004.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-1004"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "fac7cdb1-3d9d-387f-a33d-5002569fc8d0",
              "name": "\"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability: Unescaped User-Controlled Data in HTTP Response is a common vulnerability in web applications. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is written to HTTP response without proper sanitization. For example, in the following code snippet:\n\n```go\nwriter.Write(serialized)\n```\n\nIf `serialized` contains user-controlled data and is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in HTTP response. This can be done using Go's `html/template` package which automatically escapes user-controlled data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the above code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(string(serialized))\nerr := t.Execute(writer, nil)\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.Parse` function parses the user-controlled data and `template.Execute` function writes the parsed data to HTTP response. This ensures that the user-controlled data is properly escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go. It provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "fb4328f8-f000-36dc-9c31-8f217f6e80c9",
              "name": "Unsanitized User-Influenced Filename Vulnerability in Content-Disposition Header",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsanitized User-Influenced Filename Vulnerability in Content-Disposition Header\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when user-influenced data is used to construct a filename in the `Content-Disposition` HTTP header without proper sanitization. This can lead to various attacks such as HTTP response splitting, HTTP header injection, or other injection attacks.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when using the `Set` method of the `Header` type from the `net/http` package to set the `Content-Disposition` header with a filename that includes user-influenced data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to sanitize user-influenced data before using it to construct a filename. This can be done by removing or encoding special characters that can be used to manipulate the HTTP header or the filename.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"net/url\"\n)\n\n// ...\n\nfilename := url.PathEscape(name)\napiContext.Response.Header().Set(\"Content-Disposition\", fmt.Sprintf(\"attachment; filename=%s.zip\", filename))\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, the `PathEscape` function from the `net/url` package is used to percent-encode the user-influenced data before using it to construct the filename.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `net/http` package for the `Header` type and its `Set` method.\n- The `net/url` package for the `PathEscape` function.\n- The `fmt` package for the `Sprintf` function.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-113: Improper Neutralization of CRLF Sequences in HTTP Headers ('HTTP Response Splitting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-113",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-113"
                ]
              }
            },
